The most likely root cause is that the `force` parameter is not being set to a value other than `undefined`, which means it's defaulting to its initial value, potentially causing an empty search result.

In TypeScript, if you don't provide a value for a function parameter, it defaults to its initial value. In this case, since `force` has a default value of `false`, when the function is called without providing a value, `force` will be `false`. 

This could lead to an empty search result because the condition `this.qmd.searchMode === "search"` would not be met, causing the function to return `false`.

To fix this issue, you should ensure that the `force` parameter is always provided with a valid value. You can do this by adding a default value for `force` or by requiring it as an argument.

Here's how you could modify your code:

```typescript
private shouldRunEmbed(force: boolean = false): boolean {
  if (this.qmd.searchMode === "search" && !force) {
    return false;  // Skip embeddings for BM25-only mode
  }
  // ... rest of logic
}
```

Alternatively, you could require the `force` parameter:

```typescript
private shouldRunEmbed(force: boolean): boolean {
  if (this.qmd.searchMode === "search" && !force) {
    return false;  // Skip embeddings for BM25-only mode
  }
  // ... rest of logic
}
```

In this case, you would need to call the function with a valid value for `force`, like so:

```typescript
this.shouldRunEmbed(true);  // Run embedding even in search mode
this.shouldRunEmbed(false); // Skip embedding in search mode
```

